  <!-- THE GAS FIRE PROBLEM, UNIQUE SECTION -->
  <section class="pf-section" style="background:#f1f5f9;">
    <div class="container">
      <span class="pf-section-label">ST HELENS LANDLORD KNOWLEDGE</span>
      <h2>Your St Helens CP12 Must Cover the Gas Fire. Not Just the Boiler.</h2>
      <p class="pf-sub">This is the single most common compliance mistake in St Helens rental properties. A CP12 that inspects only the boiler and leaves the gas fire unchecked is legally incomplete, even if it looks complete and you paid for it.</p>

      <div style="display:grid;grid-template-columns:1fr;gap:1.5rem;margin-top:2rem;">

        <div class="pf-card pf-card-left-red">
          <strong style="display:block;color:var(--navy);font-size:1rem;margin-bottom:0.35rem;">Why WA10 Victorian Terraces Create This Problem</strong>
          <p style="font-size:0.93rem;color:var(--muted);margin:0 0 0.75rem;line-height:1.65;">The Victorian terraces of St Helens Town, Parr, Thatto Heath and Sutton were built with a fireplace in the living room. Many of these properties had the original coal fires replaced with gas fires decades ago, and many still have them in active use as landlord-supplied appliances today. The Gas Safety Regulations 1998 are explicit: every gas appliance supplied by the landlord as part of the tenancy must be individually inspected and recorded on the CP12. A gas fire in the living room counts. A back boiler behind the fire counts. A gas hob in the kitchen counts.</p>
          <div style="background:#fef2f2;border:1px solid #fecaca;border-radius:var(--radius-sm);padding:0.75rem 1rem;">
            <p style="font-size:0.88rem;color:#7f1d1d;margin:0;font-weight:600;">If your St Helens rental property has a gas fire and your CP12 only lists the boiler, you may not be legally compliant, even if the certificate was issued by a Gas Safe registered engineer. We inspect every gas appliance in the property in one visit.</p>
          </div>
        </div>

        <div class="pf-card pf-card-left-orange">
          <strong style="display:block;color:var(--navy);font-size:1rem;margin-bottom:0.35rem;">The Section 21 Risk of an Incomplete Certificate</strong>
          <p style="font-size:0.93rem;color:var(--muted);margin:0;line-height:1.65;">An incomplete CP12, one that misses a gas appliance, is not a valid CP12 under the Gas Safety Regulations. A landlord who serves a Section 21 notice while holding an incomplete certificate faces the same legal exposure as a landlord who has no certificate at all. Courts have been clear that a certificate that does not cover every gas appliance in the property does not satisfy the statutory obligation. For St Helens landlords with properties containing gas fires, this is not a theoretical risk. We cover every appliance in one visit on one certificate.</p>
        </div>

        <div class="pf-card pf-card-left-orange">
          <strong style="display:block;color:var(--navy);font-size:1rem;margin-bottom:0.35rem;">What We Check in a Single St Helens Visit</strong>
          <p style="font-size:0.93rem;color:var(--muted);margin:0;line-height:1.65;">We inspect every gas appliance in your St Helens rental property in a single visit, boiler, back boiler, gas fires, gas hobs, gas cookers and any other gas-connected appliance supplied by you as the landlord. Each appliance is inspected individually, given a result and recorded on the CP12. The certificate covers the whole property, not just the boiler. The digital document is emailed the same day for you to forward to your tenant immediately.</p>
        </div>

      </div>
    </div>
